					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251587" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609807190 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Jan 2021 00:39</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4862349">
									

<p>I feel like there's kind of 2 questions here.</p>
<p>In regards to leadership, there is a hierarchy, it's just not interesting enough to mention in many stories. Think about the O5's (and the Ethics Committee, who have similar power) like the board of a corporation or president of a state, and fill in all the boring jobs beneath them. Site Directors are the next down in power, and there are many stories on the wiki that involve the end of the world that show Sites still independently functioning.</p>
<p>For the essence, I agree with Nagiros that research is a core practice. The Foundation believes in the status quo, and the status quo objective way to understand the world is science. Beyond that, if you learn to understand an anomaly, then it is no longer anomalous (even if you don't plan to let the world know.) I picture the Foundation as being very academic, with scientists working on many different SCPs collaborating and publishing and sharing knowledge. See <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/kate-mctiriss-s-personnel-file">Kate Mctiriss's</a> articles for a little taste of this.</p>
<p>If you want the super broad answer, the core essence is Secure, Contain, Protect. Secure and Contain refer to anomalies, while Protect refers to anomalies (from outside forces), humanity (from anomalies), and normalcy (from even knowledge of anomalies).</p>

							</div>

								
					
