				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251587" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1610117017 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Jan 2021 14:43</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865198">
									

<p>No problem! Yeah, people have a lot of different views off the Foundation. I think some people headcanon that each SCP's research team is super-isolated and nobody even discusses their SCP with anyone else due to security. That doesn't make sense to me, but to each their own.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>They probably would look like how you described them as an academic place.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That reminds me of <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/excerpt-from-the-astrolabe-institute-journal">this tale</a>, where I think something almost exactly like that happened. (It's both Broken Masquerade and the Lethe doomsday canon, and <em>I think</em> the idea is that people forgot about the Foundation.)</p>
<blockquote>
<p>they most likely store it but it made me think that there is a possibility that they give it to humanity to improve the condition of the world but that depends on how you look at the foundation. thank you for responding!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's also what I believe: things get designated as explained (-EX) and then potentially slowly leaked to the public. I think we just don't have many articles showing that on it wiki because they'd most likely be boring and hard to write.</p>

